    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm studying for my physics final and im kinda stuck on quantum entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? i dont need the heavy math right now just a conceptual explanation",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a bizarre, yet fascinating, phenomenon where two or more particles become linked in such a way that they share the same fate, no matter how far apart they are. Imagine two of these linked particles, and if you measure a property of one—say, its spin—you instantly know the corresponding property of the other. This is fundamentally different from classical correlation, which is like having two matching gloves in separate boxes; you know they match because they were *set* to match beforehand. In entanglement, the particles don't have a definite state until the moment of measurement, and the measurement on one instantaneously influences the other.",
      "source": "target",
