    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. but i heard someone call it \"spooky action at a distance\" once. why do people use that term? it's kind of a weird way to describe physics, right?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Spooky action at a distance\" is the phrase Einstein used, and it perfectly captures the deeply unsettling nature of entanglement! He found it so counterintuitive that it seemed to violate the principle that nothing can travel faster than the speed of light. It's spooky because the correlation appears instantaneous, as if the particles are communicating faster than light, which, to Einstein, was deeply problematic. It's a bit like a massive, highly advanced, and very strange thought experiment that makes even the smartest physicists scratch their heads.",
      "source": "target",
